    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-04-21T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-04-21T15:00:00-05:00" n="223"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d223">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Korea)/4–1249: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d223fn1">Mr. Muccio presented his credentials as American
                        Ambassador to the Republic of Korea on April 20, 1949.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-04-21T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 21, 1949—3 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>268. Army has furnished fol comments re points raised last three paras <gloss
                        target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 374 Apr 12:</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Problem estab arsenal for repair Jap weapons and mfr ammo therefor must be
                        resolved in <gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss> where necessary Jap machinery
                        presumably available.<note n="2" xml:id="d223fn2">Concerning U.S. support of
                            the arsenal program, see Sawyer, <hi rend="italic">Military Advisors in
                                Korea</hi>, p. 99.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>45 US vessels now “on loan” Korean <gloss target="#t_CG1">CG</gloss> being
                        transferred <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> under <gloss
                            target="#t_OFLC1">OFLC</gloss> (Warx 85775 Mar 18).<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d223fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Requisitions for maintenance items and spare parts now being filled
                        partially (about $35,000) from Army stocks while remainder consisting spare
                        parts <gloss target="#t_CG1">CG</gloss> vessels and other strictly marine
                        items (about $200,000) now before <gloss target="#t_JMAC1">JMAC</gloss> as
                        matter priority for decision as to which <gloss target="#t_Dept1"
                            >Dept</gloss> of <gloss target="#t_NME1">NME</gloss> will provide. </item>
                    <pb facs="0408" n="994" xml:id="pg_994"/>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>The sum tentatively allocated Korea under pending mil assistance program
                        insufficient purchase additional patrol boats at $1.4 million each (even in
                        unlikely event they available) without seriously depleting funds required
                        for maintenance other components.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Request for arsenal has been recd by Army from Min Defense. Additional
                        technical info requested from <gloss target="#t_CG1">CG</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_USAFIK1">USAFIK</gloss> thru <gloss target="#t_CINCFE1"
                            >CINCFE</gloss> (Warx 85456 Mar 8)<note n="4" xml:id="d223fn4">Not
                            printed.</note> upon receipt which request will be submitted <gloss
                            target="#t_JMAC1">JMAC</gloss> consideration.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>20 liaison-type planes have been provided of which 15 understood
                            operational; no others contemplated. No plans exist for transfer
                            transport aircraft to <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>.</p>
                        <p>End Army comments.</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Subj receipt ur comments State will endeavor expedite decisions paras 3 and 5 and
                    will look further into 4 and 6.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
